# LAMMPS Input File
# Licensed under CC BY 4.0
# A Set of Materials-Science Tutorials for the LAMMPS Simulation Package
# Modernized recreation of the MSU/CAVS tutorials by Mark A. Tschopp
# Tutorial 10: generalized stacking fault energy (gamma-line) of fcc aluminum.
#
# A (111)-oriented slab is cut in two along a (111) plane.  The upper half is
# rigidly displaced along the [11-2] direction by increasing fractions of the
# in-plane lattice repeat; at each displacement the atoms are relaxed ONLY
# perpendicular to the fault plane (in z), and the excess energy per unit area
# is the generalized stacking fault energy gamma.  Tracing gamma versus the
# displacement gives the gamma-line, whose local minimum is the intrinsic
# stacking fault energy (ISF) and whose first maximum is the unstable stacking
# fault energy (USF).
#
# Strategy (compare Tutorials 2 and 6): the ideal slab is written once to a
# data file; a loop then reloads it, applies the TOTAL shift for that step,
# relaxes, and appends one record to a structured YAML file.  Reloading the
# ideal slab every step keeps the displacements independent (no drift).

# crystallographic orientation: x=[1-10], y=[11-2], z=[111] (the fault normal)
# Material is selected through three index variables, so the identical script
# runs any fcc metal by overriding them (GUI "Set Variables" dialog or -var):
#   default (aluminum):  Al_zhou.eam.alloy, element Al, a0 = 4.08165 Ang
#   copper:  -var pot Cu_mishin1.eam.alloy -var elem Cu -var lat 3.61493
variable pot  index Al_zhou.eam.alloy
variable elem index Al
variable lat  index 4.08165          # relaxed lattice constant (Angstrom)

units metal
boundary p p s                       # free surfaces in z: a single fault plane
atom_style atomic
lattice fcc ${lat} orient x 1 -1 0 orient y 1 1 -2 orient z 1 1 1
lattice fcc 4.08165 orient x 1 -1 0 orient y 1 1 -2 orient z 1 1 1
Lattice spacing in x,y,z = 5.7723248 6.6653065 7.0696252
# The in-plane lattice repeat along [11-2] is a0*sqrt(6)/2; LAMMPS' oriented
# y-cell is 4/3 of it, so the box is commensurate with the shifted crystal
# only when the number of y-cells is a multiple of 3 (here 6 = 8 repeats).
# A non-multiple gives a strained, artificially high stacking-fault energy.
region box block 0 4 0 6 0 8
create_box 1 box
Created orthogonal box = (0 0 0) to (23.089299 39.991839 56.557001)
  1 by 1 by 1 MPI processor grid
create_atoms 1 box
Created 3200 atoms
  using lattice units in orthogonal box = (0 0 -0.0056557001) to (23.089299 39.991839 56.562657)
  create_atoms CPU = 0.001 seconds
pair_style eam/alloy
pair_coeff * * ${pot} ${elem}
pair_coeff * * Al_zhou.eam.alloy ${elem}
pair_coeff * * Al_zhou.eam.alloy Al
Reading eam/alloy potential file Al_zhou.eam.alloy with DATE: 2007-10-12
write_data slab.data
System init for write_data ...
Neighbor list info ...
  update: every = 1 steps, delay = 0 steps, check = yes
  max neighbors/atom: 2000, page size: 100000
  master list distance cutoff = 12.1025
  ghost atom cutoff = 12.1025
  binsize = 6.05125, bins = 4 7 10
  1 neighbor lists, perpetual/occasional/extra = 1 0 0
  (1) pair eam/alloy, perpetual
      attributes: half, newton on
      pair build: half/bin/atomonly/newton
      stencil: half/bin/3d
      bin: standard

# one in-plane repeat along [11-2] is a0*sqrt(6)/2; the Shockley partial that
# creates the intrinsic stacking fault is one third of it, b_p = a0/sqrt(6).
# The fault plane is placed in a (111) gap near the slab middle; its height
# scales with the (111) interlayer spacing a0/sqrt(3).
variable period equal ${lat}*sqrt(6.0)/2.0
variable period equal 4.08165*sqrt(6.0)/2.0
variable zcut   equal 11.5*${lat}/sqrt(3.0)
variable zcut   equal 11.5*4.08165/sqrt(3.0)
variable np equal 25                 # number of displacement steps over one period
variable conv equal 16021.766        # eV/Ang^2 -> mJ/m^2

print "# gamma-line of fcc ${elem} (${pot}), shift along [11-2] on (111)" file gsfe.yaml screen no
print "# shift in Angstrom; pe in eV; area in Ang^2; period = ${period} Ang" append gsfe.yaml screen no

variable k loop 0 ${np}
variable k loop 0 25
label loop
  clear
